SIMPLE: expiate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Expiate
<hw>Ex"pi*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Expiated</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Expiating</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>expiatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>expiare</ets> to expiate;
<ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>piare</ets> to seek to appease, to purify with
sacred rites, fr. <ets>pius</ets> pious. See <er>Pious</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To extinguish the guilt of by sufferance of penalty or
some equivalent; to make complete satisfaction for; to atone for; to
make amends for; to make expiation for; <as>as, to <ex>expiate</ex> a
crime, a guilt, or sin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>expiate</qex> his treason, hath naught left.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Treasurer obliged himself to <qex>expiate</qex> the
injury.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To purify with sacred rites.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither let there be found among you any one that shall
<qex>expiate</qex> his son or daughter, making them to pass through the
fire.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xviii. 10 (Douay version)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expiate</ent>⟦br⟧

